The Persian empire, dating from Cyrus (B.c. 559), was destroyed by Alexander, but the Roman poets use Persae and Medi generally of any Oriental people‚ but especially, as here, of the Parthians who occupied what had been the Persian empire. By defeating and destroying Crassus at Chartae (Chai-ran, Acts vii. 2) Β.ο. 53 and captui-ing the Roman standai-ds, they had made a deep impression on the imagination of the Romans.
